2015-07-14 00:42:46,355 INFO [localhost-startStop-1] [SchemaUpdate] schema update complete

h3. Workaround
# Stop Bamboo
# Run the SQL against the Bamboo database
{noformat}
ALTER TABLE REPOSITORY_CHANGESET MODIFY CHANGESET_ID VARCHAR(255);
ALTER TABLE USER_COMMIT MODIFY COMMIT_REVISION VARCHAR(255);
ALTER TABLE DEPLOYMENT_VERSION_COMMIT MODIFY COMMIT_REVISION VARCHAR(255);
{noformat}
# Start Bamboo

Currently the DB columns for passwords in Bamboo are VARCHAR(255). Given the encryption employed by Bamboo this limits password length to 183 characters. EX:

initial password (183 char): {code}ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ0123456789ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ0123456789ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ0123456789ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ0123456789ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ0123456789ABC{code}

Once this password is passed to Bamboo (via the IMSERVER table for this example) the hashed password looks like:
hashed password in DB before import (248 char): {code}m2nxNxQVySj2pvrtpn4jHPiHbwFeoGjQBaKXPVvv1vWwgEmxA3JnUanHcKbsS+yG9OhczobOxEha2JP/aHaB7i1mbbJS0MVpm2nxNxQVySj2pvrtpn4jHPiHbwFeoGjQBaKXPVvv1vWwgEmxA3JnUanHcKbsS+yG9OhczobOxEha2JP/aHaB7i1mbbJS0MVpm2nxNxQVySj2pvrtpn4jHPiHbwFeoGjQBaKXPVvv1vVbn8p8EB/MtA=={code}

Now this will work fine in Bamboo, but should you create a value that exceeds 183 characters the encryption will output a value that's 256 characters long and Bamboo will fail to store it in the DB, throwing this error:
{code}
2015-07-07 11:40:44,358 WARN [http-bio-8085-exec-9] [JDBCExceptionReporter] SQL Error: 0, SQLState: 22001
2015-07-07 11:40:44,358 ERROR [http-bio-8085-exec-9] [JDBCExceptionReporter] ERROR: value too long for type character varying(255)
{code}

(!) This part can be worked around by manually updating the db schema such that this column is of type TEXT instead of VARCHAR

However the fairly nasty part of this issue is when you try to export Bamboo with an overly long password value. Since the import process overwrites any schema changes the password will always be stored in a VARCHAR(255) type column. This causes problems because the import process further lengthens the password value. Here is the SAME password value as the first two from the error message of a failed import (344 char):
{code}{code}

With this situation the import will ALWAYS fail as the string is forced into a VARCHAR(255) type but will always exceed the character limit as the import process overwrites any DB schema changes.

Currently the only workarounds for this issue are to return to your original instance and remove the offending string or manually dig through your DB export and remove it, only to add it back after the import process is complete. This may not be feasible in all cases depending on the data.

If the latest build result does not have a completed date, time based expiry will not run. 

h5. Steps to replicate
# Disable all agents
# Start a plan and watch it go into queue
# Shutdown Bamboo
# Restart Bamboo
# Run a time based expiry (example: expire builds more than 1 day ago)

This message shows up in the log for the tested plan:
{noformat} Last build completed date for 'com.atlassian.bamboo.chains.DefaultChain@185ba707:com.atlassian.bamboo.chains.ChainResultsSummaryImpl@c161b50e' is null. No builds will be expired.{noformat}

h5. Analysis
This behavior is caused by the following code in {{bamboo/components/bamboo-core/src/main/java/com/atlassian/bamboo/build/expiry/BuildExpiryBeanImpl.java}}
{code}if (lastBuildDate == null)
           {
               log.warn("Last build completed date for '" + plan + ":" + lastResultsSummary + "' is null. No builds will be expired.");
               return 0;
           }{code}

h5. Workaround
Re-run the build and stop it immediately so that a completed date appears.
